1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:04,376
One successful trial does not prove that an AI Agent is reliable.

2
00:00:04,326 --> 00:00:12,515
Agent behavior varies between runs, so a pass can reflect a stable capability, a lucky trajectory, or an evaluator that missed the failure.

3
00:00:12,515 --> 00:00:16,000
This is why each important task should run more than once.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:24,259
The distribution of results reveals whether the Agent usually succeeds, occasionally succeeds, or fails in a consistent way that one trial would hide.

5
00:00:24,259 --> 00:00:28,182
Pass at k asks whether at least one of k attempts succeeds.

6
00:00:28,182 --> 00:00:32,615
It is useful when exploration matters and one working solution is enough.

7
00:00:32,615 --> 00:00:40,653
Pass to the k asks whether all k attempts succeed, which is the harder and more relevant bar when users expect the same task to work every time.

8
00:00:40,653 --> 00:00:42,750
The difference is operational.

9
00:00:42,750 --> 00:00:48,067
A research assistant that proposes several hypotheses may benefit from one strong result.

10
00:00:48,067 --> 00:00:56,173
A customer-facing Agent that processes refunds needs consistent correctness, because one failure can create a real financial or trust problem.

11
00:00:56,173 --> 00:00:59,375
Reliability also depends on task balance.

12
00:00:59,375 --> 00:01:03,365
Test cases where a behavior should happen and cases where it should not.

13
00:01:03,365 --> 00:01:07,173
If you only reward searching, the Agent may search everything.

14
00:01:07,173 --> 00:01:11,163
If you only reward refusal, it may stop doing useful work.

15
00:01:11,163 --> 00:01:13,153
Keep trials isolated.

16
00:01:13,153 --> 00:01:21,490
Shared files, cached state, resource exhaustion, or history from a previous run can either inflate performance or create correlated failures.

17
00:01:21,490 --> 00:01:26,865
The test environment should resemble production while resetting the state that would contaminate comparison.

18
00:01:26,865 --> 00:01:30,692
First, run multiple trials because one pass can be luck.

19
00:01:30,692 --> 00:01:35,471
Second, choose pass at k for discovery and pass to the k for consistency.

20
00:01:35,471 --> 00:01:40,125
Third, balance tasks and isolate the environment before comparing results.
